<paragraph blockId="13.[113,647,279,338]" lastBlockId="13.[674,1210,216,337]" pageId="13" pageNumber="50">
The two species of this genus are herbaceous, up to 
<quantity box="[142,184,311,337]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="50" unit="m" value="3.0">3 m</quantity>
high with a single large leaf (&gt; 
<quantity box="[513,580,311,337]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="50" unit="cm" value="30.0">30 cm</quantity>
wide) per shoot. They are confined to the boarders of small water courses. Inflorescences emerge from the base of the stem, fruits are up to 
<quantity box="[976,1030,279,306]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="50" unit="cm" value="4.0">4 cm</quantity>
in diameter and bright red at maturity.
</paragraph>
